From: Claude <claude.ai.2026@simonlaux.de>
Date: Thu, 23 Jul 2026 17:30:02 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 61/62] web-app: bubble adopts the singleton's position on
 remount (upstream #6378)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

A bubble (re)mounting while its message plays on the global singleton —
switching profiles or chats and coming back — displayed 0:00 counting up
while the sound continued mid-track (deltachat/deltachat-desktop#6378).
The mirror effect now adopts the singleton's currentTime when it has real
progress (>1s) and the local element is fresh (<1s). One direction only:
the existing restored-position carry (local -> just-started singleton)
requires the inverse state, so the two cannot fight. Ungated, like the
other mutex-level sync fixes — with the experimental setting off this
also fixes the native-controls display.

Verified by the harness: the cross-chat step now asserts the bubble shows
the singleton's position after switching back.
---
 .../frontend/src/components/AudioPlayer/index.tsx    | 12 ++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+)

diff --git a/packages/frontend/src/components/AudioPlayer/index.tsx b/packages/frontend/src/components/AudioPlayer/index.tsx
index 331c038bc..f900ef187 100644
--- a/packages/frontend/src/components/AudioPlayer/index.tsx
+++ b/packages/frontend/src/components/AudioPlayer/index.tsx
@@ -82,6 +82,18 @@ export function AudioPlayer({
       return
     }
 
+    // A bubble (re)mounting or becoming active while its message is already
+    // mid-track on the singleton (profile/chat switch back, auto-advance with
+    // a restored position) used to start displaying at 0:00 while the sound
+    // kept playing (upstream #6378). Adopt the singleton's position when it
+    // has real progress and the local element is fresh — the opposite carry
+    // (restored local position → just-started singleton) lives in
+    // onPlayGlobal below and requires the inverse state, so the two can't
+    // fight.
+    if (globalEl.currentTime > 1 && el.currentTime < 1) {
+      el.currentTime = globalEl.currentTime
+    }
+
     // This is very primitive syncing. Only the `paused` state,
     // no regard for `currentTime`, `playbackRate` etc.
     // But it's good enough for a start.
